150-214. The teacher of declamation fares no better for all his patient toil and is held responsible for the stupidity of the pupil, who refuses to pay his fee till compelled by law. Men have costly houses and expensive servants, but regard a trifle as too much for the leacher of their sons. A few have made money, but only by sortune's caprice. Once a teaoher was held in awe by his pupils; now he may even suffer persona] violence at their hands.
